passages.text: August 31, 2025 07:54 PM GMT
We provide further analysis on France, with scenarios and cross- market targets. The macro portfolio is unchanged but we reshuffle the bond RV recommendations.

- Inflation forwards reached multi-month highs this week but we do not believe the move is warranted. We still favor short-end longs.- Euro curves steepening stalled but not elsewhere. We still recommend 10s30s steepeners.- We provide further analysis on French debt in a follow-up to the ad hoc piece. Short dated OATs may come under pressure.- In derivatives we close OE OW vs Estr, present our views on the Eurex rolls and highlight the different behavior of Estr-Euribor and 3s6s bases.- Supply corner: We preview September EA supply, highlighting an active month ahead with syndications in focus after a relatively calmer August.
Please add me to your distribution list.

German yields are almost unchanged on the week, but inflation markets (Exhibit 2) and EGB spreads provided more excitement.

1y1y HICPxT pushed close to March highs this week, with the move showing disconnection with oil prices. Back in March the driver was the surprise German fiscal announcement, whereas this week a domestic factor is lacking.

This week's inflation releases came broadly in line with expectations. The minutes of the July ECB meeting confirmed the preference for a wait- and- see approach whilst leaving some room for further easing if necessary amid split views on the inflation outlook (Exhibit 3).
Exhibit 2: 1y1y HICPxT has reached new highs since March despite subdued oil prices
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research

Exhibit 3: The minutes of the July ECB meeting confirmed the preference for a wait-and-see approach, whilst leaving some room for further easing if necessary amid split views on the inflation outlook\*

From the ECB July meeting minutesMixed views on the inflation data...Several members viewed inflation risks as tilted to the downside relative to the June staff projections, at least for the next two years.A few members judged risks to be tilted to the upside relative to the June staff projections, especially over the medium term.... argue for wait and seeWhile a view was expressed that the current conditions would also be consistent with a further rate cut, owing to increasing downside risks to output and inflation, keeping interest rates unchanged was seen as a robust approach to managing shocks and two-sided inflation risks across a wide range of plausible scenarios. Overall, there was currently a high option value to waiting for more information and the resolution of some uncertainty.
Source: ECB, Morgan Stanley research. \\* Selected extracts from accounts of the ECB July meeting

Inflation forwards might have rallied in sympathy with US ones, but we believe the overseas catalyst (fear about fiscal dominance) does not really apply to the euro area and we reiterate our preference for trading the short end of the curve from the long side (Oct- Dec ECB flattener, received 1y1y Estr).
Despite ongoing steepening in UK and US, curve segments in euro did not do much. We still recommend 10s30s steepeners with a target of 30bp in 6s.

The risk- on impulse from Powell's dovish delivery was somewhat offset by the increased uncertainty in French politics. We covered the interaction of French politics and EGBs in two pieces: France 2026 Budget: Deja Vu? Maybe Not (published July 9) and A Vote on 8 September, and What's Next (published August 27). Exhibit 4 shows what topics we covered in those for reference.

Trades: we keep our recommendations: 1) overweight 9Y Spain vs Belgium (or France as an alternative), and 2) overweight 4Y Greece vs Germany. See below on spillover risks. For investors who want to express a negative view on France we flag that the short end widening has been more modest than in any of the three widening episodes in the last year (Exhibit 5) and short dated OATs might come under pressure on any renewed weakness.
**Exhibit 4:** Covered topics in our recent notes (linked above) on the interaction of French politics and EGBs

Source: Morgan Stanley Research
**Valuations**: as shown in Exhibit 6, current French spreads appear to be incorporating a political discount and/or premium for rating downgrades.

**Scenarios and targets**: We believe there is scope for retracement if/when the budget gets approved, by Bayrou or another PM. Under such scenario, we can see the 10y France-Italy spread moving back to last week's levels (~8bp through, looking at recent bonds and adjusting for the curve). Similarly, we would expect the spread to Germany to retrace toward the 65bp area.

In event of early elections, we can see France potentially trade wider than Italy (a tweak to the Obp target in the July piece to reflect market moves since then) as uncertainty is prolonged. The 10y France-Germany spread could potentially widen to the 95bp area.

**Spillover risks**: Exhibit 7 shows that in two of the three periods of France-induced pressure (July, September and November of last year), 10y Italy-Germany spreads were tighter a week after French spreads peaked.
**Exhibit 6:** OAT/Bund is already incorporating a political discount
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research. i-spreads regressed against 2026 EC forecasts for debt/GDP and deficit/GDP and rating index (average of Fitch. Moody's and S&P)
**Exhibit 7:** 10y Italy-Germany spreads were tighter a week after French spreads peaked in 2 out of 3 episodes in 2024
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
This dynamic is similar to the aftermath of the sovereign debt crisis: issues in one country can prompt sympathy widening elsewhere but eventually the moves are faded by investors.
Our original plan was to publish a new set of intra- EMU spread forecasts this week but given the binary risk posed by French politics we postpone the exercise.

Politics did not stop with France. In the Netherlands another party left the coalition a few weeks ahead of the 29 October election, with limited market impact. We expect negotiations to form a new government to take a long time given the fragmentation of the political landscape and historical precedents.
Exhibit 8: Dutch PFs have accumulated a decent percentage of \(10y+\) Dutch bonds over the years
Source:DNB,Morgan Stanley Research. \(\%\) of Dutch PFs holding over total holdings
Exhibit 9: The low-coupon BTPS 3/41 is cheap vs the interpolated curve with the 3/40 and 9/43
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research

Market- wise we have been neutral on Dutch bonds. We expect only limited domestic demand for the new 30y NETHER to be issued on September 23. Dutch pension funds have accumulated a decent percentage of \(10y+\) Dutch bonds over the years (Exhibit 8) and we see less support going forward under the new regime.

We did not expect the RAGB long end to be affected as much as NETHER and we recommended a box flattener vs Germany to fade the 30y cheapening in Keep Long- end Steepeners, Add EGBs RV Exposure Via Intra- EMU Curve Boxes. A syndication in the 7y sector should have helped the trade, but it hit the stop level and we now close the position.
In RV we recommend taking profit on the RV fly in Spain (opened in Window for Carry Trades?) and we hit the stop level on the Italy green fly.

We flag the cheapness of the low- coupon BTPS 3/41 vs the interpolated curve with the 3/40 and 9/43 (- 71%/+100%/- 29% fly, Exhibit 9). All these bonds were issued as 20y benchmarks. We recommend fading this cheapness and see the main risk to the trade being a lack of mean reversion.
Future basis: we published recently our Eurex roll analysis for the Sep/Dec cycle. We summarize our views in Exhibit 10.

Longs should roll early.- Bobl roll: Mildly bearish directionality, small longs outstanding on the front contract.- Bund roll: Positioning on the front contract is short. Shorts should roll early.- Buxl roll: Residual optionality on the back contract. Shorts on the front contract have been covered recently.- BTS roll: Mildly bearish directionality. Long positioning on the front contract. Longs should roll early.- BTP roll: Positioning is long on the front contract. Longs should roll early.- OAT roll: Residual shorts outstanding on the front contract

ASW: This week we saw a mild re- widening on German spreads, predominantly led by the 5y sector (see Exhibit 11). Part of the move was motivated initially by the French headlines, prompting a tentative risk- off in price action with a stabilization thereafter.

We note as well, that this year continues to follow the trend noted during the August tightening seasonal (see Exhibit 12) with a small retracement to marginally wider ASWs heading into the September roll, predominantly seen when positioning on duration is short (see Enter Oct- Dec Flatteners and Tactical OE ASW Wideners).
Exhibit 11: Weekly changes in German ASW
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 12: 10y Germany ASW August seasonality 2025 versus average
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
We think that our tactical recommendation to be into OEU5 vs &str wideners has largely played out at this stage and we close our trade.

Basis: In the future we will provide analysis on basis dynamics and related trades. As we expand into this area we note that the uncertainties on the macro and political front seen this week led into a widening of the Euribor/&str basis, particularly at the front- end (see Exhibit 13) as opposed to what was observed on 3s6s basis where the front- end drifted tighter during the week (see Exhibit 14).
Exhibit 13: Weekly changes in Euribor-&str fwd

Germany will issue- 9.5bn on Tuesday and Wednesday, in the bonds with maturities 9/27 and 8/35.

On Thursday, Belgium will sell bonds through Ori auction. In France a new 10y was expected and the French DMO decided to go ahead with a new 11/35 line, but at the same time reduce the issuance range to 9.5- 11bn. We see the FV for the new bond at 7.2bp over the 5/35. In general, the last OAT rolls have been cheaper than the yield spread of the previous pair (Exhibit 16) and this roll should be no exception in our view.
Finally, Spain will come to the market for \(\sim 5.5bn\)

Later in the month, Germany is expected to return with an additional \(\sim 18bn\) , plus the tap of a green bond scheduled for the second week. France and Spain will come back to the market during the third week of the month, with expected volumes broadly in line with next week's issuance. Belgium is also expected to return to the market in the third week of the month, with an additional 2.75- 3.3bn in issuance.
Exhibit 16: In general, the last OAT rolls have been cheaper than the yield spread of the previous pair
Source: Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
Among other EA countries, the Netherlands has scheduled an optional tap in the second week and plans to syndicate a new 30y bond with maturity 1/56 during the final week of the month.

Italy is expected to hold auctions in the second week, potentially issuing a new 7- year bond while tapping the 3- year. A new 10- year benchmark may come in the final week, alongside taps in the inflation- linked BTPs and the 5- year sector.
Austria and Ireland are expected to issue \(\sim 2bn\) and 0.75- 1bn, respectively, during the second week. Finland and Greece are scheduled to come to market in the third week.

In addition to scheduled auctions, as flagged last week, Italy may syndicate a new 30- year bond as early as next week. Portugal may also syndicate a new bond either in the second or fourth week. The EU is expected to issue a new bond in September, alongside a scheduled auction in the third week.
Exhibit 17: August has been a light month in terms of issuance
Source: National Treasuries, Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research
Exhibit 18: EA10: Issued vs expected remaining issuance
Source: National Treasuries, Bloomberg, Morgan Stanley Research

EA10 issuance in August totalled- €75bn, marking the lowest monthly volume of the year due to seasonal factors (see Exhibit 17). EA10 countries have now completed \(\sim 71\%\) of their 2025 funding needs (see Exhibit 18). Among the Big4 countries, Italy stands out as the least advanced in completing its funding needs, while Spain has executed a greater portion of its issuance plans.

Overweight (O). The stock's total return is expected to exceed the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12-18 months.

Equal-weight (E). The stock's total return is expected to be in line with the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12-18 months.

Not-Rated (NR). Currently the analyst does not have adequate conviction about the stock's total return relative to the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12-18 months.

Underweight (U). The stock's total return is expected to be below the average total return of the analyst's industry (or industry team's) coverage universe, on a risk-adjusted basis, over the next 12-18 months.
